'''Shidami Ōtsuka Kofun''' (志段味大塚古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun|qq=}} located in {{ill|Moriyama-ku, Nagoya|ja|守山区|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriyama-ku, Nagoya|qq=}}, {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aichi Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. It is part of the {{ill|Shidami Kofun Group|ja|志段味古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shidami Kofun Group|qq=}}, Historic Site1 as a National Historic Site.
== Overview == Shidami Ōtsuka Kofun is the largest {{ill|zenpō-kōen-fun|ja|前方後円墳|lt=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|comment=doing this because I need to differentiate it in piped links too with my new interwiki tool as not the ambiguous phrase keyhole shaped kofun|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/zenpō-kōen-fun|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenpokoenfun|qq=}} (keyhole-shaped tumulus) within the ancient Kofuns scattered around the Ōgute Pond area. Historically referred to as "Ōtsuka No. 1 Kofun," it has undergone several phases of investigation and conservation.
The tumulus was first excavated in 1923 by Suematsu Umehara of Kyoto Imperial University, revealing a {{ill|clay coffin|ja|粘土槨|1=Clay coffin chamber|1=Clay coffin chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/clay coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Clay coffin chamber|qq=}} burial facility and numerous grave goods. However, the site remained largely neglected until surveys by Nagoya University in 1982-83 and further research by Nagoya City Board of Education starting in 2005. Despite these efforts, significant degradation occurred due to the passage of time.
A significant discovery in 2008 revealed a second burial facility parallel to the mound's axis, distinct from the earlier documented structure.
== burial and area == The tumulus is a {{ill|scallop-shaped tumulus|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=Scallop Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/scallop-shaped tumulus|13=User:Immanuelle/Scallop Kofun|qq=}} with a short anterior portion. Its area are as follows: * Total length of the mound: approx. 55m (approx. 62m including moat) * Diameter of the rear circular portion: approx. 40m * Height of the rear circular portion: approx. 7m * Height of the anterior portion: approx. 1.5m
The mound features terraced levels on the rear circular section, a surrounding stone-paved base, and a partial haniwa arrangement. A moat encircles the tumulus in a horseshoe configuration.
== burial ==
=== Primary burial === The primary burial discovered in 1923 contained grave goods including bronze mirrors and weapons. The burial orientation is believed to face northeast based on the arrangement of grave goods.
=== Secondary burial === The secondary burial unearthed in 2008 featured a mortuary pit measuring 5.8m in length and 3m in width, with an adjacent passage-like structure. It likely housed a carved wooden coffin painted with vermilion pigment.
== burial goods == burial goods from the tumulus are housed in various institutions: * '''Kyoto University Museum''': ** Bronze mirrors ** Gilded belt fittings ** Iron arrowheads ** Horse fittings ** Weapons * '''Nagoya City Museum''': ** Armor fragments ** Haniwa fragments * '''Miharashidai Archaeological Museum''': ** Waterfowl-shaped haniwa ** Chicken-shaped haniwa ** Cylindrical haniwa ** Pottery fragments
== Access == * From {{ill|Ōzone Station|ja|大曽根駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōzone Station|qq=}} (JR Chūō Line, Meitetsu Seto Line, Nagoya City Subway Meijō Line): ** Take the {{ill|Nagoya Guideway Bus Line|ja|名古屋ガイドウェイバス志段味線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagoya Guideway Bus Line|qq=}} (Yutorīto Line) to "Shintōyabashi-Minami." * From {{ill|Kōzōji Station|ja|高蔵寺駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōzōji Station|qq=}} (JR Chūō Line, Aichi Loop Line): ** Take the Nagoya City Bus, Shidami Circulation Route, to "Shidami Ōtsuka Kofun." == See Also == * {{ill|List of kofun in Japan|ja|Infobox ancient site一覧|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/List of kofun in Japan|qq=}}
== References == {{reflist}}
